{"timestamp": "2025-12-12 11:20:35.526015", "event": "llm_end", "text": "**Network Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report**\n\n| Item | Observation | Assessment |\n|------|-------------|------------|\n| **BGP Routing Tables** | <ul><li>Leaf router 0 0 (AS 65200) advertises 10.0.1.0/24 via **172.16.0.8** (not a directly‑connected neighbor).</li><li>Leaf router 0 1 (AS 65201) advertises 10.0.0.0/24 via **172.16.0.10** and **172.16.0.6** (neither is a directly‑connected neighbor).</li><li>Spine routers and the super‑spine advertise correct next‑hops (directly‑connected /31 links).</li></ul> | **Anomaly** – leaf routers are advertising routes with next‑hops that are not reachable from them. This indicates a mis‑configured BGP neighbor or wrong IP address in the BGP configuration on the leaf routers. |\n| **Host Connectivity** | <ul><li>Ping from **pc_0_0** (10.0.0.2) to **pc_0_1** (10.0.1.2) returns “Destination Host Unreachable” from 172.16.0.7.</li><li>Ping from **pc_0_1** to **pc_0_0** fails with “Network is unreachable.”</li></ul> | **Symptom** – hosts in different leaf subnets cannot reach each other. The error originates from the leaf router that should forward the traffic (leaf router 0 0 for pc_0_0 → pc_0_1, leaf router 0 1 for pc_0_1 → pc_0_0). |\n| **Routing Path Analysis** | <ul><li>pc_0_0’s default route is via leaf router 0 0 (10.0.0.0/24). To reach 10.0.1.0/24 it relies on the BGP route advertised by leaf router 0 0, which points to 172.16.0.8 – a non‑existent neighbor.</li><li>pc_0_1’s default route is via leaf router 0 1 (10.0.1.0/24). To reach 10.0.0.0/24 it relies on the BGP route advertised by leaf router 0 1, which points to 172.16.0.10 / 172.16.0.6 – again non‑existent neighbors.</li></ul> | **Root Cause** – The leaf routers have incorrectly configured BGP next‑hop IPs. Because the next‑hop is unreachable, the routers drop the packets, leading to the observed host‑to‑host failures. |\n| **Other Observations** | <ul><li>Spine routers and the super‑spine show clean, single‑path BGP tables with correct next‑hops.</li><li>No obvious ARP or interface status issues were reported (all interfaces appear up in the BGP tables).</li></ul> | **Conclusion** – The problem is isolated to the leaf routers’ BGP configuration; the rest of the topology is functioning as expected. |\n\n### Summary\n\n1. **Anomaly detected** – Leaf routers advertise routes with next‑hops that are not directly connected to them.  \n2. **Fault localization** – The mis‑configured BGP entries are on **leaf_router_0_0** and **leaf_router_0_1**.  \n3. **Root cause** – Incorrect BGP neighbor IPs or wrong next‑hop configuration on the leaf routers, causing unreachable traffic between hosts in different leaf subnets.\n\nNo further investigation is required at this stage; the issue is clearly identified and localized.", "generation_info": {"model": "gpt-oss:20b", "created_at": "2025-12-12T11:20:34.528650698Z", "done": true, "done_reason": "stop", "total_duration": 26849050241, "load_duration": 68288254, "prompt_eval_count": 4760, "prompt_eval_duration": 161786212, "eval_count": 2757, "eval_duration": 26194178338, "model_name": "gpt-oss:20b"}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 4760, "output_tokens": 2757, "total_tokens": 7517}}
